Objects.Name: FabApp
Objects.Description:
A registered project, application, or business that has direct access to the Fabric API.

An App's primary purpose is to facilitate [[User|Object|FabUser]] interaction with Fabric. To accomplish this, an App typically creates an interface for its [[Users|Object|FabUser]]. This interface hides the complex details of the Fabric API, and instead provides intuitive features like custom inputs, searches, summaries, and visualizations. 

When a [[User|Object|FabUser]] becomes a [[Member|Object|FabMember]] of an App, they are granting that App permission to perform various actions on their behalf (via the App's interface). It is vital for an App to provide each [[User|Object|FabUser]] with a positive experience and do nothing to violate the [[User|Object|FabUser]]'s trust.

Every App has a special 'Data Provider' [[Member|Object|FabMember]], which is typically controlled by that App's administrator. The 'Data Provider' allows the App to interact with Fabric as itself (rather than on behalf of a particular [[User|Object|FabUser]]).

Every item added to Fabric is associated with (via [[Member|Object|FabMember]]) a [[User|Object|FabUser]] and and an App. Thus, Fabric can determine which App is responsible for any particular item, enforce applicable access rights, analyze the data for a particular App or [[Member|Object|FabMember]], etc.

An object which is able to (via [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] connections) accumulate meaning, context, user sentiment, and relationships.  Artifacts and [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]] are the central components of the Fabric architecture.

There are no restrictions on what an Artifact can represent.  Fabric encourages the generous use of [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]] to identify and describe each new Artifact. Ideally, the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] connections will distinguish an Artifact from all others.

Objects.Name: FabClass
Objects.Description:
Represents any item (real, imaginary, virtual, conceptual, or otherwise) that an [[App|Object|FabApp]] or [[User|Object|FabUser]] can define and/or use to generate meaning. Classes and [[Instances|Object|FabInstance]] are closely related, and are the primary method for generating new [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]].

A Class represents a particular group, type, set, or category of items. Each Class must uniquely identifiable (via name and disambiguation) amonst all other Classes.
[(EX|Ellie's [[Class|Object|FabClass]] Example|Ellie is building an [[App|Object|FabApp]] for dog lovers, but there are not yet animal-related Classes for Ellie to use. She first creates broad Classes (like 'Animal', 'Mammal', and 'Canine') and relationships between them (like 'Canine is a Mammal').

She then creates narrower Classes for each dog grouping (like 'Working Dog') and breed (like 'Great Dane'), adding relevant relationships along the way. A Class named 'Boxer' already exists, but it has a sports-related meaning. She adds a new 'Boxer' Class with a 'Dog Breed' disambiguation value to resolve this conflict.)]

Properties.Name: Disamb
Properties.Description: A secondary label or identifier, used to resolve unique-name conflicts.

Properties.Name: Name
Properties.Description: A descriptive name or title.

Properties.Name: Note
Properties.Description: A summary of the Class's intended meaning or purpose. This can resolve confusion in cases where a Class has vague or missing [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]].

Objects.Name: FabDescriptor
Objects.Description:
A [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] Element that describes and refines the relationship between the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s two [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]]. Descriptors are the only required [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] Element.

First, the [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]] provides semantic meaning to the relationship, such as: a A "is a" B, or C "sounds like" D. Since this relationship is directional (flowing _from_ the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and _to_ the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]]), the [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]] must coordinate correctly with the relationship's direction.
[(EX|Relationship Example|_Objective:_
Describe that a circle is a shape. 

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Circle' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Shape' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The Descriptor uses the 'Is A' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Circle ... Is A ... Shape.)]

Descriptors also offer optional (but powerful) refinement capabilities, which allow a Descriptor to be very specific. Using any [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]], a Descriptor may refine the [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]], the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]], and/or the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]]. Note: while these [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] links are discussed here in the context of a Descriptor, the actual traversal links exist with the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]].
[(EX|Refinement Example|_Objective:_
Describe that car A and car B have headlights with a similar shape.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Car A' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Car B' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The Descriptor uses the 'Is Similar To' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]], uses 'Headlight' to refine both [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]], and uses 'Shape' to refine the [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Car A (more specifically, its) Headlight ... Is Similar To (more specifically, by) Shape ... Car B (more specifically, its) Headlight.)]

Properties.Name: TypeId
Properties.Description: Specifies the type of relationship or connection.

Objects.Name: FabDirector
Objects.Description:
A [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] Element that creates a directional, action-based flow between the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s two [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]].

The nature of a Director's pathway depends on its [[DirectorType|Enum|DirectorType]]. The Director can  represent a factual, well-defined path, a virtual link, a suggested flow, etc.

A Director specifies a [[DirectorAction|Enum|DirectorAction]] for each of the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]], which give additional meaning to the Director's pathway. The primary action is meant to be performed on the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] before the pathway begins. The related action is meant to be performed on the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] after the pathway ends.
[(EX|Defined Pathway Example|_Objective:_
Direct along the defined pathway of listening to a particular album's third and fourth songs (song C and D) in order.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Song C' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Song D' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'IsRelatedTo' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]].
- The Director uses the 'Defined Path' [[DirectorType|Enum|DirectorType]] and the 'Listen' [[DirectorAction|Enum|DirectorAction]] for each [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Song C ... Is Related To ... Song D. (The) Listen (action on) ... Song C ...  (leads to the) Listen (action on) ... Song D ... (via) Defined Path.)] [(EX|Suggested Pathway Example|_Objective:_
Direct along a suggested pathway of listening to song A and then learning about that song's vocalist, singer B.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Song A' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Singer B' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'IsRelatedTo' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]].
- The Director uses the 'Suggested Path' [[DirectorType|Enum|DirectorType]], the 'Listen' primary [[DirectorAction|Enum|DirectorAction]], and the 'Learn' related [[DirectorAction|Enum|DirectorAction]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Song A ... Is Related To ... Song B. (The) Listen (action on) ... Song A ... (leads to the) Learn (action on) ... Singer B ... (via) Suggested Path.)]

Properties.Name: PrimaryActionId
Properties.Description: Specifies the action to be performed on the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].

Properties.Name: RelatedActionId
Properties.Description: Specifies the action to be performed on the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].

Properties.Name: TypeId
Properties.Description: Specifies the type and reason for the pathway.

Objects.Name: FabEventor
Objects.Description:
A [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] Element that applies the concept of time to a particular [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]].

An Eventor places a [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] at a specific point in time and describes why it is significant to the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]. The [[EventorType|Enum|EventorType]] provides this significance, establishing that this particular point in time is when the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] started, occurred, is expected, etc.

Each Eventor represents one particular point in time, however, the precision of that point in time can vary. The [[EventorPrecision|Enum|EventorPrecision]] allows a point in time to specify a level of accuracy ranging from one second to one year.
[(EX|Started Example|_Objective:_
Specify that Albert Einstein was born (i.e. started his life) on March 14, 1879.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Albert Einstein' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Life' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Has A' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]]. 
- The Eventor uses 'March 14, 1879' as its DateTime value, the 'Started' [[EventorType|Enum|EventorType]], and the 'Day' [[EventorPrecision|Enum|EventorPrecision]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Albert Einstein ... Has A ... Life, ... (an event which) Started ... (on the) Day ... March 14, 1879.)] [(EX|Expected Example|_Objective:_
Specify that person A plans to attend college B in the year 2024.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Person A' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'College B' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Participates In' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]] and the 'Attend' [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] to refine it.
- The Eventor uses '2024' as its DateTime value, the 'Is Expected' [[EventorType|Enum|EventorType]], and the 'Year' [[EventorPrecision|Enum|EventorPrecision]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Person A ... Participates In (more specifically, by) Attend(ing) ... College B, ... (an event which) Is Expected (to occur) ... (in the) Year ... 2024.)]

_Note: every [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] recieves a timestamp upon creation. This timestamp is not related to the Eventor._

Properties.Name: DateTime
Properties.Description: A particular point in time, with a level of accuracy defined by EventorPrecision.

Properties.Name: PrecisionId
Properties.Description: Specifies the level of accuracy given to this point in time.

Properties.Name: TypeId
Properties.Description: Specifies the significance of this point in time.

Objects.Name: FabFactor
Objects.Description:
Provides a specific piece of information, knowledge, or opinion about a pair of [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]]. Factors and [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]] are the central components of the Fabric architecture.

A Factor forms a directional relationship from its primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] to its related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]]. It contains one or more components, called Factor Elements. Each Element has a specific ability to refine, describe, and/or supplement this [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] relationship in a meaningful way.

There are six Factor Elements: [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]], [[Director|Object|FabDirector]], [[Eventor|Object|FabEventor]], [[Identor|Object|FabIdentor]], [[Locator|Object|FabLocator]], and [[Vector|Object|FabVector]]. The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] is the only required Element; the rest are optional. A Factor typically uses one or two Elements, but (in very complex cases) could potentially use four or more.

Just as there are no restrictions on what a particular Artifact can represent, there are no restrictions on the type of meaning or information a Factors can provide. A [[FactorAssertion|Enum|FactorAssertion]] allows a Factor to specify that it represents (among other things) a fact or an opinion. This level of confidence for a particular [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] allows [[Users|Object|FabUser]] and [[Apps|Object|FabApp]] to more effectively find the type of information they desire.

Properties.Name: Completed
Properties.Description: The date/time of completion. This value is null if the Factor is not complete.

Properties.Name: Created
Properties.Description: The date/time of creation.

Properties.Name: Descriptor
Properties.Description: This element defines the relationship between the primary and related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].

Properties.Name: Director
Properties.Description: This element creates a directional pathway between the primary and related [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]].

Properties.Name: Eventor
Properties.Description: This element applies the concept of time.

Properties.Name: FactorAssertionId
Properties.Description: Specifies the type of information and/or level of confidence.

Properties.Name: FactorId
Properties.Description: Uniquely identifies this object amongst all other objects of this type.

Properties.Name: Identor
Properties.Description: This element applies a name or identifier.

Properties.Name: IsDefining
Properties.Description: Specifies whether this Factor helps to directly and uniquely define the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].

Properties.Name: Locator
Properties.Description: This element provides a geographical or relative position.

Properties.Name: Note
Properties.Description: A summary of the Factor's intended meaning or purpose. This is useful in cases when the Factor is vague, complex, or confusing. It can help resolve issues in cases where the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s Elements inaccurately model the intended meaning. Typically, this value is not written directly by a [[User|Object|FabUser]]; the [[App|Object|FabApp]] should have enough information about a particular Factor-creating action to form a reasonable sentence or phrase.

Properties.Name: Vector
Properties.Description: This element applies a numeric axis and value.

Objects.Name: FabIdentor
Objects.Description:
A [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] Element that applies a name or identifier to a particular [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]].

An Identor attaches a text-based value to a [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]. This value can represent a a full name, a nickname, a globally-unique identifier, a reference key to some other system, etc.

The [[IdentorType|Enum|IdentorType]] hints at the purpose or intent of the Identor. A "Text" [[IdentorType|Enum|IdentorType]] is typically meant to provide enhanced search capabilities (like finding a person by an alternate name) or some other organizational use.  A "Key" [[IdentorType|Enum|IdentorType]] is typically meant to associate a [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] with some external system (like a Product ID from an online store) or to provide an [[App|Object|FabApp]] with a "reverse lookup" for their own internal IDs.
[(EX|Alternate Name Example|_Objective:_
Identify that Grand Valley State University is also known as (has the alternate name of) 'Grand Valley'.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Grand Valley State University' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Name' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Has A' DescriptorType, and an 'Alternative' [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] to refine the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The Identor uses 'Grand Valley' as its text value, and the 'Text' [[IdentorType|Enum|IdentorType]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Grand Valley State University ... Has A ... Name (more specifically, an) Alternative, ... (identified by the) Text ... 'Grand Valley'.)] [(EX|Abbreviation Example|_Objective:_
Identify that Grand Valley State University is also known as (has the abbreviation of) 'GVSU'.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Grand Valley State University' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Abbreviation' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Has A' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]]. 
- The Identor uses 'GVSU' as its text value, and the 'Text' [[IdentorType|Enum|IdentorType]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Grand Valley State University ... Has A(n) ... Abbreviation, ... (identified by the) Text ... 'GVSU'.)] [(EX|Identifier Example|_Objective:_
Identify that game A is accessible in store B via its ID, which is '123a-45678'.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Game A' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Store B' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Is Found In' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]]. 
- The Identor uses '123a-45678' as its text value, and the 'Key' [[IdentorType|Enum|IdentorType]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Game A ... Is Found In ... Store B, ... (identified by the) Key ... '123a-45678'.)]

Properties.Name: TypeId
Properties.Description: Specifies the value's purpose or intent.

Properties.Name: Value
Properties.Description: A text-based value that can represent names, numbers, IDs, GUIDs, etc.

Objects.Name: FabInstance
Objects.Description:
Represents any item (real, imaginary, virtual, conceptual, or otherwise) that an [[App|Object|FabApp]] or [[User|Object|FabUser]] can define and/or use to generate meaning. [[Classes|Object|FabClass]] and Instances are closely related, and are the primary method for generating new [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]].

An Instance represents a singular, unique item. It may have a specific name, however, the name is not required to be unique. Instead, the creator should apply [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]] to make the [[Instance|Object|FabInstance]] as specific and meaningful as possible.
[(EX|Ellie's [[Instance|Object|FabInstance]] Example|_Continued from Ellie's [[Class|Object|FabClass]] Example..._

After completing her new [[Classes|Object|FabClass]], Ellie would like to add her own dog. She creates an Instance named 'Gulliver', and attaches several [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]] to make the [[Instance|Object|FabInstance]] as unique as possible. Her [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]] define that Gulliver is a Lhasa Apso breed, is owned by Ellie, and was born in September 2007.)] [(EX|Zach's [[Instance|Object|FabInstance]] Example|Zach built an [[App|Object|FabApp]] that allows users to rate restaurants and individual meals. He created [[Classes|Object|FabClass]] for restaurant chains and meal types. He also created Instances for specific restaurants (with relevant relationships for each).

When [[Users|Object|FabUser]] rate a particular meal, they also specify the restaurant, the day/time the meal was served, and the meal type. Behind the scenes, the [[App|Object|FabApp]] uses this data to construct a new Instance and its relationships. Because Zach's Instances are well-defined, one [[User|Object|FabUser]] could rate the same meal (at the same restaurant) every day, creating a unique and meaningful [[Instance|Object|FabInstance]] each time.)]

Properties.Name: Disamb
Properties.Description: A secondary label or identifier, used to resolve unique-name conflicts.

Properties.Name: Name
Properties.Description: A descriptive name or title.

Properties.Name: Note
Properties.Description: A summary of the Instance's intended meaning or purpose. This can resolve confusion in cases where an Instance has vague or missing [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]].

Objects.Name: FabLocator
Objects.Description:
A [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] Element that positions a [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] using geographic or relative coordinates.

A Locator attaches a three-dimensional coordinate to a [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]. The [[LocatorType|Enum|LocatorType]] defines the spatial context of the coordinate, supporting both geographic and relative positioning.

Geographic coordinates represent a position on a sphere, like Earth.  They use X for longitude, Y for latitude, and Z for elevation (in metres above sea level). Use zero for elevation if it is not known or specified.
[(EX|Geographic Example|_Objective:_
Specify that person A took photo B from a spot near the Eiffel Tower.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Photo B' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Person A' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Is Created By' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]]. 
- The Locator uses the 'Earth Coordinate' [[LocatorType|Enum|LocatorType]], a '2.292977' value for X, a '48.858154' value for Y, and (optionally) a '34.24' value for Z.

_Factor Phrase:_
Photo B ... Is Created By ... Person A, ... (at an) Earth Coordinate (location of) ... X (longitude) = '2.292977' ... Y (latitude) = '48.858154' ... Z (elevation) = '34.24' (metres above sea level).)]

Relative coordinates represent a position relative to the origin and size/bounds of the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]]'s primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]]. There are LocatorTypes for one, two, and three-dimensional relative coordinates. For coordinates which have:
- One dimension, use X for time or progress, and leave Y and Z equal to zero.
- Two dimensions, use X for width, Y for height, and leave Z equal to zero.
- Three dimensions, use X, Y, and Z values which correspond to the [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]]'s X, Y, and Z values. If these axes are undefined, use X for width (or breadth), Y for length (or depth), and Z for height (or elevation).
[(EX|Relative 1D Example|_Objective:_
Specify that book A refers to painting B on page 148 of 200 (about 74% of the book's length).

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Book A' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Painting B' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Refers To' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]]. 
- The Locator uses the 'Related 1D' [[LocatorType|Enum|LocatorType]], a '0.74' value for X, a '0.0' value for Y, and a '0.0' value for Z.

_Factor Phrase:_
Book A ... Refers To ... Painting B, ... (at a) Relative 1D (location of) ... X (position) = 0.74.)] [(EX|Relative 2D Example|_Objective:_
Specify that photo A includes person B near the top-right (25% from the top, 84% from the left) of the image.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Photo A' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Person B' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Refers To' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]].

The proper prodedure is to create a new [[Instance|Object|FabInstance]] for both the news article and photo. With this method:
- The news article and photo [[Instances|Object|FabInstance]] can receive [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]] independently.
- The Url should only receive [[Factors|Object|FabFactor]] related to the actual web page, its design, etc.

An [[App|Object|FabApp]]'s interface hides the complex details of the Fabric API, and instead provides intuitive features like custom inputs, searches, summaries, and visualizations. 

Users control their private account data and preferences using the Fabric website.

Every item added to Fabric is associated with (via [[Member|Object|FabMember]]) a User and and an [[App|Object|FabApp]]. Thus, Fabric can determine which User is responsible for any particular item, enforce applicable access rights, analyze the data for a particular User or [[Member|Object|FabMember]], etc.

Objects.Name: FabVector
Objects.Description:
A [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] Element that applies a meaningful numeric axis and value to a particular [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]].

A Vector attaches a numeric value to a [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]], using an arbitrary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] to define its "axis". This axis depends entiedgey upon the Vector's purpose. For example, a factual Vector might use an [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] like "Height" or "Shutter Speed". A Vector that provides an opinion might use an [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] like "Quality" or "Excitement". While the choice of an axis Artififact is not restricted, it can be beneficial to use [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]] which are other [[Apps|Object|FabApp]] or [[Users|Object|FabUser]] are already using as Vector axes. Note: while the axis [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] link is discussed here in the context of a [[Vector|Object|FabVector]], the actual traversal link exists with the [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]].

The [[VectorType|Enum|VectorType]] provides boundaries and context for the Vector's value. It can identify the value as a percentage, a level of agreement or disagreement, an opinion-based rating, or simply a plain numeric value. Each [[VectorType|Enum|VectorType]] provides additional information, such as a [[VectorRange|Enum|VectorRange]], to provide further meaning for the levels within the the allowed value boundaries.

A Vector's numeric value often reflects a measurement or a has a specific unit. Furthermore, a Vector can use [[VectorUnitPrefix|Enum|VectorUnitPrefix]] to specify an order of magnitude for the value. A Vector's value is a long integer, so the prefix is especially useful when fractional values are involved, or when the desired number is larger than a long integer.
[(EX|Small Value Example|_Objective:_
Specify that image A (which is a photo) has a shutter speed of 1/250 second.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Image A' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Photo' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Is A' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]]. 
- The Vector uses the 'Shutter Speed' [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] as the axis, the 'Positive Long' [[VectorType|Enum|VectorType]], '4' as the value, the 'Milli' [[VectorUnitPrefix|Enum|VectorUnitPrefix]], and the 'Second' [[VectorUnit|Enum|VectorUnit]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Image A ... Is A ... Photo, ... (which, along the) Shutter Speed (axis) ... (with a) Positive Long (numerical range), ... (has a value) '4' ... Milli ... Second(s).)] [(EX|Large Value Example|_Objective:_
Specify that Earth and the Andromeda Galaxy are 2.5 million light years (2.2705 x 10^22 metres) apart.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Earth' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Andromeda Galaxy' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Is Related To' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]]. 
- The Vector uses the 'Distance' [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] as the axis, the 'Positive Long' [[VectorType|Enum|VectorType]], '22,705' as the value, the 'Exa' [[VectorUnitPrefix|Enum|VectorUnitPrefix]] (represents 10^18), and the 'Metre' [[VectorUnit|Enum|VectorUnit]].

_Factor Phrase:_
Earth ... Is Related To ... Andromeda Galaxy, ... (which, along the) Distance (axis) ... (with a) Positive Long (numerical range), ... (has a value) '22,705' ... Exa ... Metre(s).)] [(EX|Negative Value Example|_Objective:_
Specify that article A mentions person B in a very unfair manner, about 80% of the maximum unfairness imaginable.

_Method:_
- The [[Factor|Object|FabFactor]] uses 'Article A' as the primary [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] and 'Person B' as the related [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].
- The [[Descriptor|Object|FabDescriptor]] uses the 'Refers To' [[DescriptorType|Enum|DescriptorType]]. 
- The Vector uses the 'Fairness' [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]] as the axis, the 'Opposable Favorability' [[VectorType|Enum|VectorType]], '-80' as the value, the default 'Base' [[VectorUnitPrefix|Enum|VectorUnitPrefix]], and the default 'None' [[VectorUnit|Enum|VectorUnit]]. This [[VectorType|Enum|VectorType]] has bounds of -100 to +100.

_Factor Phrase:_
Article A ... Refers To ... Person B, ... (which, along the) Fairness (axis) ... (with a) Opposable Favorabillity (numerical range), ... (has a value) '-80'.)]

After being multiplied by the prefix magnitude, the value must fall within the bounds specified by VectorType. Before prefix multiplication, this value must be between –9,223,372,036,854,775,808 and 9,223,372,036,854,775,807.

TraversalFunctions.Name: Back
TraversalFunctions.Description:
Returns the execution of the traversal path to a particular named alias. This alias is created using the [[As|Func|As]] function.

When traversal execution reaches a Back function step, the execution retraces (steps backwards through) the traversal path until the alias is reached. Execution then proceeds using the traversal step(s) that immediately follow the Back function step.

The return type of the Back function is determined by the return type of the corresponding alias.
[(EX|Return Type Example|_Traversal Steps_
Get a list of [[Members|Object|FabMember]]:
- /Root/ContainsMemberList/As(M)

Get a list of [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]] created by those [[Members|Object|FabMember]]:
- /Root/ContainsMemberList/As(M)/CreatesArtifactList

Retrace to the "M" alias, which returns [[Members|Object|FabMember]]:
- /Root/ContainsMemberList/As(M)/CreatesArtifactList/Back(M))]

When execution retraces the traversal path, it does so _only_ from the vertices that are currently active at the Back function step. This makes the Back function useful for complex filtering.

[(EX|Retrace Example|_Objective_
Find all the [[Members|Object|FabMember]] of a particular [[App|Object|FabApp]] (AppId = 123) that have created at least one [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]].

_Traversal Steps_
Create named alias "M" at the [[Member|Object|FabMember]] step:
- /Root/ContainsMemberList/As(M)

Continue traversing to the target [[App|Object|FabApp]]:
- /Root/ContainsMemberList/As(M)/InAppDefines/HasId(2)

Retrace to the [[Member|Object|FabMember]] list, which now contains only [[Members|Object|FabMember]] of "Great [[App|Object|FabApp]]":
- /Root/ContainsMemberList/As(M)/InAppDefines/HasId(2)/Back(M)

Continue traversing to the [[Artifacts|Object|FabArtifact]] created by these [[Members|Object|FabMember]]:
- /Root/ContainsMemberList/As(M)/InAppDefines/HasId(2)/Back(M)/CreatesArtifactList

Retrace to the [[Member|Object|FabMember]] list, which now also excludes any [[Members|Object|FabMember]] who have not created an [[Artifact|Object|FabArtifact]]:
- /Root/ContainsMemberList/As(M)/InAppDefines/HasId(2)/Back(M)/CreatesArtifactList/Back(M))]

Parameters.Name: Alias
Parameters.Description: The target named alias, which was defined by an [[As|Func|As]] function earlier in the traversal path.

Operations.Name: AccessToken
Operations.Description:
Get an OAuth access token using one of four 'flows'.  Fabric offers separate requests for these access token flows, but also provides this generic request for compatibility with the OAuth 2.0 specification.  See the other access token flows (such as the '[[Client Credentials|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientCredentials]]' flow) for information about the available OAuth flows.

An OAuth access token must be included with every Fabric API request (with the exception of the OAuth requests).  This token is the result of a successful login, an accepted [[App|Object|FabApp]] scope, a confirmed [[App|Object|FabApp]] secret code, and a confirmed authorization code.  Thus, each token is associated with a specific [[App|Object|FabApp]], [[User|Object|FabUser]], and successful OAuth process.  When included with an API request, Fabric obtains the relevant [[App|Object|FabApp]] and [[User|Object|FabUser]] ID values, and generates a response accordingly.

See [[FabOauthAccess|Object|FabOauthAccess]] for information on how to include an OAuth access token with a Fabric API request.

Parameters.Name: grant_type
Parameters.Description: Defines the desired access token flow.  The four accepted (case-sensitive) values are '[[authorization_code|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenAuthCode]]', '[[refresh|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenRefresh]]', '[[client_credentials|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientCredentials]]', and '[[client_data_provider|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientDataProv]]'.

Parameters.Name: client_id
Parameters.Description: The [[App|Object|FabApp]] ID value (an integer) for the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. This parameter is only used by the '[[Client Credentials|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientCredentials]]' and '[[Client Data Provider|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientDataProv]]' flows.

Parameters.Name: client_secret
Parameters.Description: The alpha-numeric Secret for the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. This verifies that the [[App|Object|FabApp]] itself is making the request, and not an imposter.  For this reason, the secret code should not be shared with anyone.

Parameters.Name: code
Parameters.Description: The authorization code obtained after a successful OAuth entry process. This parameter is only used by the '[[Authorization Code|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenAuthCode]]' flow.

Parameters.Name: refresh_token
Parameters.Description: The refresh token obtained after a successful '[[Authorization Code|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenAuthCode]]' access token flow.  A refresh token only applies to [[User|Object|FabUser]]-based OAuth sessions, not for [[App|Object|FabApp]]-based OAuth sessions.  This parameter is only used by the '[[Refresh|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenRefresh]]' flow.

Parameters.Name: redirect_uri
Parameters.Description: This value must be exactly the same as the redirect URI provided for the OAuth entry process.

Parameters.Name: data_prov_userid
Parameters.Description: The [[User|Object|FabUser]] ID value (an integer) for the Data Provider of the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. Upon [[App|Object|FabApp]] creation, Fabric creates a special 'Data Provider' [[User|Object|FabUser]] which the [[App|Object|FabApp]] uses for creating items in the Fabric system. This parameter is only used by the '[[Client Data Provider|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientDataProv]]' flow.

Operations.Name: AccessTokenAuthCode
Operations.Description:
This OAuth flow should be used immediately after obtaining an authorization code from the OAuth entry process. Fabric verifies the authorization code, determines the associated [[App|Object|FabApp]] and [[User|Object|FabUser]] IDs, and generates a new access token.

See [[Access Token|Oper|Oauth.AccessToken]] for general information about the OAuth process.

Parameters.Name: code
Parameters.Description: The authorization code obtained after a successful OAuth entry process. This parameter is only used by the '[[Authorization Code|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenAuthCode]]' flow.

Parameters.Name: client_secret
Parameters.Description: The alpha-numeric Secret for the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. This verifies that the [[App|Object|FabApp]] itself is making the request, and not an imposter.  For this reason, the secret code should not be shared with anyone.

Parameters.Name: redirect_uri
Parameters.Description: This value must be exactly the same as the redirect URI provided for the OAuth entry process.

Operations.Name: AccessTokenClientCredentials
Operations.Description:
This OAuth flow should be used to begin an OAuth session for your Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]]. This flow does not require an authorization code from the typical OAuth entry process.

See [[Access Token|Oper|Oauth.AccessToken]] or general information about the OAuth process.

Parameters.Name: client_id
Parameters.Description: The [[App|Object|FabApp]] ID value (an integer) for the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. This parameter is only used by the '[[Client Credentials|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientCredentials]]' and '[[Client Data Provider|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientDataProv]]' flows.

Parameters.Name: client_secret
Parameters.Description: The alpha-numeric Secret for the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. This verifies that the [[App|Object|FabApp]] itself is making the request, and not an imposter.  For this reason, the secret code should not be shared with anyone.

Parameters.Name: redirect_uri

Operations.Description:
This OAuth flow should be used to begin an OAuth session for your Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]]'s Data Provider [[User|Object|FabUser]]. This flow does not require an authorization code from the typical OAuth entry process. Note: this flow is not defined by the OAuth 2.0 specification; it is specifically designed to meet a Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]]'s OAuth needs.

See [[Access Token|Oper|Oauth.AccessToken]] for general information about the OAuth process.

Parameters.Name: client_id
Parameters.Description: The [[App|Object|FabApp]] ID value (an integer) for the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. This parameter is only used by the '[[Client Credentials|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientCredentials]]' and '[[Client Data Provider|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientDataProv]]' flows.

Parameters.Name: client_secret
Parameters.Description: The alpha-numeric Secret for the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. This verifies that the [[App|Object|FabApp]] itself is making the request, and not an imposter.  For this reason, the secret code should not be shared with anyone.

Operations.Name: AccessTokenRefresh
Operations.Description:
This OAuth flow should be used to refresh an expired access token. If the refresh token is valid, Fabric generates new access and refresh tokens for the given OAuth session. This process also invalidates the original refresh token.

[[App|Object|FabApp]]-only access tokens (obtained with the '[[Client Credentials|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenClientCredentials]]' flow) should not be refreshed; the [[App|Object|FabApp]] should simply request a new access token.

See [[Access Token|Oper|Oauth.AccessToken]] for general information about the OAuth process.

A refresh token only applies to [[User|Object|FabUser]]-based OAuth sessions, not for [[App|Object|FabApp]]-based OAuth sessions.  This parameter is only used by the '[[Refresh|Oper|Oauth.AccessTokenRefresh]]' flow.

Parameters.Description: The alpha-numeric Secret for the [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the request. This verifies that the [[App|Object|FabApp]] itself is making the request, and not an imposter.  For this reason, the secret code should not be shared with anyone.

Parameters.Name: redirect_uri
Parameters.Description: This value must be exactly the same as the redirect URI provided for the OAuth entry process.

Operations.Name: Login
Operations.Description:
This API request is unique -- it represents the entry point for Fabric's OAuth 2.0 authentication process.  Instead of making this API request directly from a Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]], the [[App|Object|FabApp]] should provide a link so that its users can load this request's URL (including the required query-string parameters) in their browser.

A web-based Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]] would typically load this OAuth entry page as a browser popup window. Once the user completes the full OAuth process (or upon an error), Fabric will redirect the browser to the [[App|Object|FabApp]]'s specified redirect URI.  This redirect includes query-string parameters that provide success or error information.
	
For a user, this OAuth process includes two steps: login and 'scope' acceptance.

The first step is login, where the user is prompted to enter their username and password. If a user has already logged into Fabric (i.e. has an active authentication cookie from Fabric) and the [[App|Object|FabApp]] has not requested 'switchMode', the login step is skipped.  Important note: login occurs on Fabric's server -- a Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]] never receives or sends a Fabric user's login credentials.

The second step is 'scope' acceptance.  The page tells the user that a particular Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]] wants to connect to their Fabric account, and briefly explains what this means to the user and the [[App|Object|FabApp]]. The user must accept or deny access.  Upon acceptance, the page redirects to the [[App|Object|FabApp]] with a 'success' message.  Upon denial, Fabric performs an error redirect.
	
Similar to the login step, if a user has already accepted 'scope' for a particular [[App|Object|FabApp]], the second step is skipped.  Thus, in the case where a user is already authenticated with Fabric and has already allowed [[App|Object|FabApp]] access, the entire process results in a success redirect.
	
See [[FabOauthLogin|Object|FabOauthLogin]] for the query string parameters that can be included in the success and error redirects.

Parameters.Name: response_type
Parameters.Description: Describes which type of authentication should be performed. For now, this value should always be 'code'. Fabric may accept more response types in the future.

Parameters.Name: client_id
Parameters.Description: The ID of the Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]] making the OAuth Login request.  The access code provided after a successful OAuth process will be associated with this [[App|Object|FabApp]] ID and the authenticated [[User|Object|FabUser]]'s ID.

Parameters.Name: redirect_uri
Parameters.Description: The URL which will receive success/error redirects from the OAuth Login process.  This URL should handle the following query-string parameters: access_code, error, error_description, state.

Parameters.Name: scope
Parameters.Description: Describes the level of access the [[App|Object|FabApp]] will have to the [[User|Object|FabUser]]'s account.  This value is required by the OAuth 2.0 specification, however, Fabric currently ignores it.  All OAuth requests currently receive the same level of access to the [[User|Object|FabUser]]'s account.  Fabric may begin using this parameter in the future.

Parameters.Name: state
Parameters.Description: Provides a security function for a Fabric [[App|Object|FabApp]].  All success/message redirect responses include a 'state' query-string parameter.  The [[App|Object|FabApp]] should check this value against the state value provided in the initial request.  The two values should always be equal. If the values are not equal, then the redirect did not come from the Fabric OAuth process (or from a different user's process), and should be handled accordingly.

Parameters.Name: switchMode
Parameters.Description: Causes the login process to behave in different ways.  If a value of '1' is provided, the user will see the login page even if they are currently authenticated with Fabric.  This is useful shared-computer scenarios, where the most-recently authenticated user may be different from the user making the current request.

Operations.Name: Logout
Operations.Description:
Terminates a particular OAuth session by invalidating the session's access token. Any further OAuth requests made with this particular access token are rejected.

Logging out of an OAuth session does not revoke the the [[App|Object|FabApp]] scope accepted by the [[User|Object|FabUser]] (during the first OAuth login process).  Furthermore, it does not end the [[User|Object|FabUser]]'s authenticated session with Fabric.  Thus, a subsequent OAuth entry by the same user may actually require zero input from the user -- they could potentially bypass both OAuth entry steps (login and scope acceptance).  This allows a user to begin a new OAuth session seamlessly, even after logging out.

Parameters.Name: access_token
Parameters.Description: The access token for the desired OAuth session. This request will fail if the token has already been invalidated by a previous logout.

Enums.Name: VectorUnitDerived
Enums.Description:
Provides conversion formulas from the [["derived" unit|Enum|VectorUnit]] to one or more [["raises" units|Enum|VectorUnit]]. Each "raises" unit receives a [[unit prefix|Enum|VectorUnitPrefix]] and an exponent value.

[(EX|Watt Example|_Description_
The Watt unit conversion is defined with three seperate VectorUnitDerived items:
- WattGram
- WattMetre
- WattSec

_Equation_
Those three items represent the Watt conversion equation:
1 Watt = 1 (Kg)*(m^2)/(s^3))]
